sons and with Thomas Becket, it was also a crucial period in the evolution of legal and governmental institutions. Here experts in the field provide significant reevaluations of its most important aspects. Topics include Henry's accession and his relations with the papacy, the French king, other rulers in the British Islesand the Norman baronage; the development of the common law and the coinage; the court and its literary milieu; the use of Arthurian legend for political purposes; and the career of the Young King Henry, while the introduction examines the historiography of the reign. CONTRIBUTORS: MARTIN ALLEN, MARTIN AURELL, NICK BARRATT, PAUL BRAND, SEAN DUFFY, ANNE DUGGAN, JEAN DUBABIN, JOHN GILLINGHAM, EDMUND KING, DANIEL POWER, IAN SHORT, MATTHEW STRICKLAND CHRISTOPHER HARPER-BILL and NICHOLAS VINCENT are Professors of Medieval History at the University of East Anglia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHenry II.  aLegal institutions.  aMedieval king.  aPolitical history.1 aAllen, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAurell, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarratt, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrand, Paul A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrand, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, Seán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuggan, Anne J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunbabin, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillingham, John B, econtributor.4ctb4https://id